<div id="review_380401461" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/380401461" />
    <a title="Lynn Joshua" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1046887-lynn-joshua"><img alt="Lynn Joshua" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514340932p2/1046887.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/380401461?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lynn Joshua" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lynn Joshua" href="/user/show/1046887-lynn-joshua">Lynn Joshua</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer380401461" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6795842081961025934">The unforgettable and tragic story of an Appalachian family lured to Detroit by the promise of high wages. Living in the heart of the industrialized north during WW II, Gertie, the strong and good wife and mother, shows determination and grace as she struggles to adjust while her dreams of self-sufficiency and personal freedoms shrink and perish. Her family is forced into dependence on the machine of industrialized society which relentlessly destroys their independence and dignity. <br/>It&apos;s a classi</span>
  <span id="freeText6795842081961025934" style="display:none">The unforgettable and tragic story of an Appalachian family lured to Detroit by the promise of high wages. Living in the heart of the industrialized north during WW II, Gertie, the strong and good wife and mother, shows determination and grace as she struggles to adjust while her dreams of self-sufficiency and personal freedoms shrink and perish. Her family is forced into dependence on the machine of industrialized society which relentlessly destroys their independence and dignity. <br />It's a classic of American 'regional' literature. <br />(The Dollmaker was a runner-up for the 1955 National Book Award (won by Faulkner with The Fable).)</span>
  <a data-text-id="6795842081961025934" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review380401461">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
        <a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link380401461" title="Flag this review as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=380401461&amp;resource_type=Review&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F600335.The_Dollmaker">flag</a>





      <span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_review_380401461'><a id="like_count_review_380401461" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/380401461?resource_type=Review"><span class="likesCount">7 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it gr-button gr-button--small" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F600335.The_Dollmaker">Like</a></span>
