  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2671543432" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2671543432" />
    <a title="Franky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2534471-franky"><img alt="Franky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1312356219p2/2534471.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2671543432?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Franky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Franky" href="/user/show/2534471-franky">Franky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534471-franky?shelf=2019-reading-challenge">2019-reading-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2534471-franky?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2671543432" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1095971481341531323">For me, this novel was very reminiscent of Steinbeck’s The Grapes of Wrath in its depiction of one family’s struggles to adapt and adjust to a new setting and situation where there are daily external and internal conflicts. We certainly see this with the Nevels, and Gertie is the one who tries to hold everything together. In the same vein as a Steinbeck novel, there is certainly an aspect of emotional investment on the part of the reader as we watch the efforts of one family to overcome financia</span>
  <span id="freeText1095971481341531323" style="display:none">For me, this novel was very reminiscent of Steinbeck’s The Grapes of Wrath in its depiction of one family’s struggles to adapt and adjust to a new setting and situation where there are daily external and internal conflicts. We certainly see this with the Nevels, and Gertie is the one who tries to hold everything together. In the same vein as a Steinbeck novel, there is certainly an aspect of emotional investment on the part of the reader as we watch the efforts of one family to overcome financial burdens, prejudice, and tragedy in their new surroundings in Detroit after leaving Kentucky. <br /><br />I think what Arnow handles so well is allowing the reader to get to know the characters. The Dollmaker is a hefty book well over 600 pages, and while some reviewers do complain about the length of the novel and the many intricacies and complexities about the daily life of the Nevels contained within the book, I think there is a sense that the author is trying to make these characters are real as possible through careful dialogue and details. <br /><br />There are some prominent themes contained within the novel as well that one could literally dissect in various ways. One of these is Gertie’s inner conflicted nature about religion and faith, as this is a repeated theme that crosses her paths many times within the scope of the novel, especially amid some painful tragedies that she must endure. Another theme that comes into focus is the contrasting of rural vs. urban life, and the adjustments the family has to make. And simply the repeated idea of having to adjust to life becomes a prominent and continuous struggle, as they family attempts to make Detroit their new home amid the ugliness they encounter. <br /><br />In total, Harriette Arnow’s The Dollmaker is quite a well-crafted social criticism, rich in prose and authentic, realistic characters who the reader feels for and can identify with by novel’s end. As stated before, it does take quite a bit of emotional investment on the part of the reader, as the novel has a good deal of pathos and sadness, but I think this adds to the power and experience of reading. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1095971481341531323" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

